text: Fun Theory/Fact: Because Dinosaurs were the large land and sea animals when the meteor struck, they were the ones to die out. The small shrew-like mammals of then survived the meteor because they burrowed underground to avoid detection by dinosaurs, which also saved them from extinction. With the dinosaurs extinct, the lack of large predators allowed the mammals to gain a foothold on the new predator-less world.  Without the meteor, who knows what would have happened to mammals on Earth, but it's likely that mammals wouldn't have been as large as they are today if kept in check by bird-reptile dinosaurs.

text: Although I will say that this movie looks very original and incredibly ambitious there were a few thoughts that flew through my mind while viewing this teaser. One of which is if dinosaurs weren't extinct, humans would cease to exist. I'm only saying this since the plot revolves around a human boy and his diplodocus companion-I think that was a diplodocus. Anyway, ever since dinosaurs went extinct, mammals were able to occupy the niche in natural selection since they were able to dig burrows during the impact. That's why creatures such as wholly mammoths, giant sloths, and neanderthals existed. If the extinction never occurred, mammals would've still hide in their burrows and natural selection would join with the more successful species which were the dinosaurs.  Despite that, I'm still going to pay $15 to see this movie in 3D

text: But... it  didn't destroy every dinosaur on earth: they're still around today, there are twice as many kinds of dinosaurs alive today as there are mammals for crying outloud!...  Sorry, I want to get excited for this new pixar movie (I know I am about inside out), but as a dinosaur fan, looking at this video, there are so many cringe worthy moments that it makes suspension of disbelief difficult, even for a cartoon.   Other people have pointed out the somewhat odd look of cartoons against realistic backgrounds, but it's more than that: The thick asteroid belt, poorly done (or just hyper-stylized?) earth, the lighting up of the asteroid from far above the atmosphere, the naked pterosaurs and theropods (though apparently there will be some feathered velociraptors, to give them some credit), the dinosaurs shown watching the flyby being long extinct at the time...¬†   Ignoring facts, I personally still don't like how the dinosaurs look: They lack detail, and remind me too much of old, archaic paintings from a hundred years ago: Tyrannosaurs with their heads held at weird angles, sauropods with pot-bellies and spaghetti necks. and so forth...    Pixar often says how they do lots of research for their movies: scuba diving for finding nemo, going to south america for up... here it seemed there was very little effort given. Or it's just more cartoony than any pixar movie before it. *shrug*    But those are just my initial thoughts... hopefully I'm being overly critical about a subject matter I care about, and it will be an enjoyable movie non the less.

text: What is up with these dinosaurs looking so inaccurate? No feathers on the carnivores and outdated body types on the herbivores? I'll forgive you Pixar, but you have no excuse for being so wrong. It looks like you used exclusively references no more recent than the 1980s. That parasaurolophus? uggh. Way to further prolong the public misconception about what these animals really looked like. And why are the dinosaurs so much more stylized than animals depicted in previous Pixar films? The animals in Nemo and Ratatoullie were stylized but still belivable because the detail matched their environments. Here they look like they belong to different movies. I don't know, it's weird. text: But what if... GoodDino?  If the Dinos weren't wiped out... humans wouldn't exist.  My theory is that these are people (probably prehistoric) that were somehow put through cryonics, and they were preserved and used as a lab experiment for future humans that could jump across parallel universes. They would put them in a parallel universe in which the earth wasn't hit by the asteroid, and all the dinosaurs are still living. This is one reason why the Dinosaurs look so animated and unreal, because they have evolved (for whatever reason) to look like that. Back to the future humans, they would just study what the prehistoric people did.  These future humans might be trying to figure out their past, how they became so smart, etc., and also put down obstacles in the prehistoric people's way, not only to study them, but also introduce further plot into the movie.  If you actually read it, congrats! I probably overthought this. Put your weird theories about what happens in the replies section.

text: Well, if dinosaurs hadn't been wiped out by the asteroid, then mammals wouldn't have evolved in ways so as to take their place, and reptiles would have been the primary large land animals for much longer, meaning that bison and humans (still) wouldn't have coexisted with dinosaurs.¬† Except that dinosaur biodiversity was already decreasing even long before the impact, meaning their days were already numbered, and most sauropods (especially Apatosaurus) were already extinct by the end of the Cretaceous.¬† And then not to mention that evolution would just keep going and any notable length of time later there would be no recognizable species left at all, having been completely replaced by new ones.¬† I really want to like this, but logical cause-and-effect does not just shut off in a "what if" alternate timeline hinged around a single divergence point.
